article.description:
Underestimating Sheri Sam's range proved
costly for the Charlotte Sting.
article.headline: Sam breaks loose for 23 points, five 3-pointers
article.linkText: Sam suddenly gets hot outside hand for Miami
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Underestimating Sheri Sam's range proved
costly for the Charlotte Sting.

	   Sam made a season-high five 3-pointers and scored 23 points to
lead the Miami Sol to a 66-55 victory over Charlotte on Tuesday
night.

	   Charlotte, which could have broken a tie with Orlando for second
place in the Eastern Conference, had no idea Sam could be so good
from long range. After all, she came into the game with just 10
3-pointers, and only one in the first two games against the Sting.

	   ''Sheri Sam was on fire and her perimeter shots opened it up for
their inside game,'' Charlotte guard Dawn Staley said. ''She helped
hit the perimeter shots in the first half and went to work on the
inside in the second half.''

	   Sam made all five of her attempts and was 9-for-13 from the field
to lead Miami (7-10). Miami was 8-for-10 from 3-point range.

	   ''My shot felt good tonight,'' Sam said. ''I had some wide-open
shots and was able to knock them down. I credit my teammates for
getting me the ball when I was so wide open.''

	   Ruth Riley and Betty Lennox each scored 10 points for Miami,
which avoided a three-game sweep to Charlotte (9-8).

	   Charlotte was doomed from the start because of off-nights from
Andrea Stinson and Allison Feaster.

	   Stinson, Charlotte's leading scorer at 14.1 points a game,
didn't score her first basket until she made a 3-pointer as the
shot clock expired with 17:19 left in the second half.

	   She finished with four points on 1-for-5 shooting.

	   ''Stinson's a great player, but we gave a great team defensive
effort and really tried to limit a lot of her touches,'' Sam said.

	   Feaster, who averages 11.7 points and leads the WNBA in
3-pointers, scored just nine points. She was 2-for-9 from the
field, including 2-for-4 from behind the arc. She has made a 3 in
six consecutive games and in all but one this season.

	   Charlotte was just 5-for-14 from 3-point range.

	   ''Defending the 3 was one of our biggest keys,'' Miami coach Ron
Rothstein said. ''In the previous two games, we would get to their
shooters and stop. We would let them shoot. Not letting them shoot
was a huge key.''

	   Stinson and Feaster's poor nights forced Charlotte Smith and
Staley to pick up the offensive load, something neither was
equipped to do.

	   Staley, the first Sting player to ever be voted a starter in the
All-Star Game, led Charlotte with 13 points. Smith, a defensive
specialist, had 10.

   ''We were just flat,'' Stinson said. ''It was one of those
nights, defensively and offensively we were flat.''

	   Miami led most of the game, but Feaster pulled Charlotte to 41-40 on her first 3 of the game with 13:30 to play. But the Sol
took control by scoring 15 consecutive points in a 19-1 run that
Charlotte couldn't recover from during a five-minute scoring
drought.

	   The Sting cut it to 60-50 on Smith's jumper with 3:13 to play
and Feaster closed it to 60-53 on a 3, but the Sol got a basket
from Riley and four free throws from Sandy Brondello to seal the
victory.
